Chapter 7: First-Person Plural

Chapter 7: First-Person Plural

The letter of resignation was a single sheet of government-issue paper, but it felt like a stone tablet in my hand. The scent of the damp office—stale coffee, ozone from the old computer, the ghost of industrial cleaner—was suddenly precious. This room had been my cage and my sanctuary for three years. I laid the paper on the desk, the click of the pen unnaturally loud. My signature, usually a hurried scrawl, I drew with deliberate, archaeological care: Elara Vance, Ph.D. Each stroke was a trowel scraping away the sediment of my old life.

Dr. Armitage’s face, when I handed it to him, did not crumple in anger but in a profound, disappointed exhaustion. “This is professional suicide, Elara. Not just here. Everywhere. They’ll blacklist you.”

“I know.”

“For what? A doomed legal crusade and a…” He trailed off, unable to voice the assumption about Kaelen that hung in the air like humidity.

“For the right translation,” I said, my voice steadier than I felt. The academic in me needed him to understand. “You taught me that context is everything. That a word without its world is a corpse. I was studying a corpse. Now I’m trying to help a world.”

He looked at the resignation, then out the grimy window at the eucalyptus grove that separated the compound from the valley. “They’ll come for your notes. Your copies.”

“They’re mine. My personal field journals. The funding agreement is specific.”

“They’ll argue otherwise. They’ll bury you in litigation until you’re a footnote in your own life.” He pinched the bridge of his nose. “Walk out that door, and you are alone.”

That was the final, clean cut. The loneliness he invoked was the old kind, the sterile, academic isolation I knew how to survive. The thought of a different loneliness—of walking away from the valley, from the smell of woodsmoke in Kaelen’s hair, from Anuka’s voice weaving stories in the firelight—was unendurable. “I’m not alone,” I said, and the truth of it was a physical warmth in my chest.

I left the compound at dusk. I did not look back. The crunch of gravel under my boots gave way to the soft, silent dust of the valley path. The air changed, shedding the metallic tang of bureaucracy for the green scent of taleweed and damp earth. I carried a single box: my personal laptop, three cloth-bound notebooks, and the carved river-stone Kaelen had given me weeks ago, smooth and heavy as a promise.

**

The tribal council gathered in the longhouse, the air thick with the smoke of the central fire and a tension so sharp I could taste it, like iron on the tongue. I stood before them, the box at my feet. The faces watching me were not hostile, but they were not open either. They were a landscape of weathered patience, waiting to see if this rain would nourish or flood.

Kaelen was there, at the far side of the circle. We had not spoken since the fight three days prior, a brutal, whispered thing in the rain where he’d accused me of holding back, of having one foot in their world and one in the other, and I’d spat back that he was asking me to choose between my life’s work and his. The space between us now felt wider than the valley.

“You have left your post,” Elder Maris stated. It wasn’t a question.

“I have.”

“Why stand before us now?”

I knelt, opening the box. I lifted the notebooks. “These are my personal journals. They contain my preliminary translations of the Lioran Codex, specifically the Caldera Deeds. The government’s translation is… incomplete. It ignores conditional clauses, poetic modifiers that aren’t decorative—they’re legal. They define stewardship, not ownership. The deed doesn’t say the land was sold. It says it was entrusted, with a clause for return if the waters ever sickened.”

A murmur rippled through the room, like wind through dry grass. Anuka, seated beside Maris, gave the faintest nod.

“The government will say this is stolen property,” I continued. “They will come after me for it. So, I am giving it to you. Not as a consultant. Not as an outsider. You can submit it as evidence from your own cultural archives, from a scholar you’ve retained. If it’s mine, they can fight me for it. If it’s yours…” I placed the notebooks on the woven mat in the center of the circle. “It’s harder to steal from a people than from a person.”

The silence that followed was absolute, save for the crackle of the fire. Kaelen was staring at me, his eyes reflecting the flames. I saw the anger in them soften into a painful, wary hope.

Elder Maris leaned forward. “And what do you ask in return, Elara Vance?”

“A place at the table,” I said, my throat tight. “A chance to finish the work. Not for my career. For the record.”

Anuka spoke, her voice the sound of the river over stone. “The word she uses in her heart is not ‘place.’ It is ‘home.’ She has burned her bridge. There is no ‘their’ for her anymore. Only ‘us.’” She looked at Kaelen, then back at me. “The question is for all of us. Do we make space at our fire?”

The debate that followed was in Lioran, a swift, flowing current of argument and assent I could only partially follow. I stood in the eye of it, feeling the push and pull of their decision like a change in atmospheric pressure. Kaelen’s voice rose once, clear and firm, a single phrase: “She carries the words.”

Finally, Maris raised a hand. She looked at me. “You will be our translator. You will sit with our lawyers. You will eat at our hearth. Your fight is our fight. Our fight is yours.” She gestured to the space beside Kaelen. “Sit.”

The shift from ‘you’ to ‘our’ was a seismic tremor in my soul. As I crossed the circle and lowered myself onto the cushion next to Kaelen, our shoulders not quite touching, the tension between us didn’t vanish. It transformed. It was no longer a wall, but a charged space, a synapse waiting to fire.

“You gave up everything,” he murmured, his eyes on the council members now discussing logistics.

“I was given everything,” I whispered back.

His hand found mine under the fold of my shawl. His fingers were calloused, warm, and they laced through mine with a finality that felt like a new grammar. The council saw, and no one looked away.
We worked in the old schoolhouse, now the nerve center of the lawsuit. The night before the final briefs were due, the room was a landscape of paper and desperation. Coffee steamed from chipped mugs. The single overhead light buzzed like an insect trapped in time. Our team—Mira, the fierce young environmental lawyer from the city, Tomás, the tribe’s historic preservation officer, Kaelen, and I—were islands in a sea of documents.

Kaelen and I were bent over my notebooks and the corresponding maps. His knowledge was somatic, lived in the body; he could point to a contour on the map and tell me the story of the landslide that shaped it, the name of the flower that bloomed there for one week each spring. My knowledge was lexical, etched in symbols. Together, we were building a dialectic of defense.

“Here,” I said, my voice hoarse. “The modifier ‘elen-ei.’ The government translated it as ‘in perpetuity.’ But in the story Anuka told about the wedding of the River and the Stone, ‘elen-ei’ means ‘for as long as the song is sung.’ It’s contingent. It requires a singer.”

Kaelen’s eyes lit with a fierce understanding. “So the entrustment clause isn’t void if the water is poisoned… it’s void if the song of the water is forgotten. If the relationship is broken.” He grabbed a fresh legal pad. “The breach isn’t environmental. It’s cultural. The mine didn’t just pollute the water; it broke the covenant of the song.”

It was a beautiful, risky argument. Poetic law. We crafted it through the night, our earlier estrangement burned away in the furnace of shared purpose. Our disagreements were swift, technical, and productive. He would challenge my interpretation with a proverb; I would counter with a syntactic precedent from a parallel clause. We were speaking two languages that had, miraculously, found a third between them.

During a lull, while Mira and Tomás argued in heated whispers over case law, Kaelen brought me a fresh cup of bitter, strong tea. “You need to sleep,” he said.

“So do you.”

He leaned against the table, looking down at me. The fatigue on his face was etched deep, but his gaze was clear. “When you placed those notebooks in the circle… I felt like I could breathe again. For the first time since you arrived.”

“I was always on your side.”

“I know. But there’s a difference between being on a side and being of a people.” He reached out, his thumb brushing a smudge of ink from my cheekbone. The touch was electric in the quiet, pre-dawn gloom. “You are of us now, Elara. For better or worse.”

The simplicity of it undid me. I leaned my head against his arm, breathing in the scent of him—woodsmoke, sage, and the dry paper of the legal pads. “It’s the only ‘we’ that has ever made sense to me,” I confessed, the words raw.

He bent and kissed my forehead, a solemn, sealing gesture. Around us, the work continued, but for that moment, we were a single, quiet fact in the chaos.

By the time the first grey light bled into the sky, the brief was complete. It was a monster, a hybrid creature of cold legal citations and the vibrant, living stories of the Liora. My translations, with Anuka’s narratives woven through as explanatory footnotes, formed its beating heart. We had argued that the very language of the deed required an understanding of the Lioran worldview, and that by ignoring it, the government and Axiom had acted in bad faith from the start.

Mira hit ‘send’ on the encrypted file to the court with a triumphant, exhausted slap to the ancient keyboard. We sat in stunned silence, the sudden absence of urgency a physical void.

Tomás stood, stretching. “We have done all we can. Now, we sleep. The fight is in the judge’s hands.”

We stumbled out into the cool, pink morning. The valley was coming alive, birdsong stitching the air together. Kaelen walked me to the guest cabin—my cabin, still, though the word felt wrong now. At the door, he didn’t ask to come in. He simply pulled me to him, his arms wrapping around me with a crushing, grateful strength. I buried my face in the hollow of his neck, feeling the rapid pulse of his heart against my lips. We stood there for a long time, two tired soldiers on a quiet battlefield, holding each other up.

“Whatever happens,” he said into my hair, “this was worth it. You were worth it.”

Sleep, when it came, was black and depthless.
It was Mira who woke me, her pounding on the door not frantic, but grimly deliberate. The sun was high, harsh. I opened the door, squinting.

Her face was pale, all professional fury. She held out a tablet. “They’ve responded. Axiom filed a countersuit this morning.”

My blood, still thick with sleep, went cold. “Against the tribe?”

“Against the tribe. And,” she said, her voice dropping into a register of pure, icy anger, “a separate, personal suit against you, Elara. For misappropriation of trade secrets, breach of contract, and misuse of government-funded intellectual property.”

The words were dry, legal, but they landed like blows. I took the tablet. There was my name, in stark, official typeface: Dr. Elara Vance, Defendant. The document alleged I had “knowingly and willfully” used proprietary data, the product of a federal grant, to “foment and support frivolous litigation” for personal gain and “due to an alleged romantic entanglement with a principal of the plaintiff.”

They had made it about me. They had made it about us*. The hook was set, and it was barbed.

I looked up from the screen, out past Mira to where Kaelen was already striding across the clearing, having heard the news. His expression was storm-dark, protective, but beneath it, I saw a flicker of the old fear—the fear that he, and his people, would be the ruin of me.

The morning air, so sweet moments before, now tasted of ash and litigation. The ‘we’ we had built so carefully in the dark of the night now had a target painted directly on its chest. My new lexicon, so painstakingly assembled, had just been defined by my enemies. And the battle, I realized, my hand tightening on the cold metal of the tablet, had just become profoundly, terrifyingly personal.